webpackJsonp([0xfeb35708bf67],{741:function(e,n){e.exports={data:{post:{id:"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2020-02-26--azfunc-v3/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/azfunc3-52663bc6c0010d24966d5439cdc6f172-b70ec.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 46.916666666666664%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;"\n        alt="extend"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/azfunc3-52663bc6c0010d24966d5439cdc6f172-48538.png"\n        srcset="/static/azfunc3-52663bc6c0010d24966d5439cdc6f172-bed0f.png 200w,\n/static/azfunc3-52663bc6c0010d24966d5439cdc6f172-5fd34.png 400w,\n/static/azfunc3-52663bc6c0010d24966d5439cdc6f172-48538.png 800w,\n/static/azfunc3-52663bc6c0010d24966d5439cdc6f172-b70ec.png 1200w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h1>Introduction</h1>\n<p>In this post, I will talk about Azure Functions 3.0 that has become generally available (GA) and was announced almost a month ago <a href="https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/updates/azure-functions-runtime-30-is-now-available/">here</a>. I feel that this is a nice update, allowing for newer function runtime and also some performance improvements. The new capabilities in the release include support for <code class="language-text">Node 12</code> and <code class="language-text">.Net Core 3.2</code>. </p>\n<p>If you are familiar with me, you know I will focus on <code class="language-text">Node.js</code> and TypeScript today.</p>\n<h1>Speaking of versions</h1>\n<p>As you can see in the table below, the runtime you use gives you different options regarding which versions of the available platform. So if we have a Node.js <code class="language-text">Function App</code> running <code class="language-text">Node 6</code>, we cannot just upgrade to a <code class="language-text">2.x</code> or <code class="language-text">3.x</code>, since that Node version is not supported.</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Language</th>\n<th>1.x</th>\n<th>2.X</th>\n<th>3.x</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>JavaScript</td>\n<td>Node 6</td>\n<td>Node 8 &#x26; 10</td>\n<td>Node 10 &#x26; 12</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>C#</td>\n<td>.Net 4.7</td>\n<td>.Net Core 2.2</td>\n<td>.Net Core 3.2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>PowerShell</td>\n<td>N/A</td>\n<td>PS Core 6</td>\n<td>PS Core 6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>TypeScript</td>\n<td>N/A</td>\n<td>GA</td>\n<td>GA</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>And just to clarify, TypeScript transpiles to JavaScript, so TypeScript versions have the same options regarding Node versions as JavaScript does.</p>\n<p><a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/sv-se/azure/azure-functions/functions-versions#languages">Table source</a></p>\n<h1>Backward compatibility</h1>\n<p>Microsoft claims that previous versions of Azure Functions should be able to run in the version 3.x runtime without changing the code. They claim the latest release to be very backward compatible.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Users running on earlier versions of Azure Functions will continue to be supported and we’re not deprecating either 1.0 or 2.0 at this time. Customers running Azure Functions targeting 1.0 or 2.0 will also continue to receive security updates and patches moving forward—to both the Azure Functions runtime and the underlying .NET runtime—for apps running in Azure. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<h1>Possibility to move between versions</h1>\n<p>The default version for creating Function Apps via <code class="language-text">Azure CLI</code> or the <code class="language-text">Azure Portal</code> is the <code class="language-text">3.x</code> version. If you look at this picture from the <code class="language-text">Function app settings</code> you can see that <code class="language-text">1.x is grayed out</code>, but both 2.x and 3.x is available.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/runtime2-71fab03e81d8c582d9f0d0d4a13d8ccd-7ad69.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 82.53223915592028%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;"\n        alt="runtime"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/runtime2-71fab03e81d8c582d9f0d0d4a13d8ccd-48538.png"\n        srcset="/static/runtime2-71fab03e81d8c582d9f0d0d4a13d8ccd-bed0f.png 200w,\n/static/runtime2-71fab03e81d8c582d9f0d0d4a13d8ccd-5fd34.png 400w,\n/static/runtime2-71fab03e81d8c582d9f0d0d4a13d8ccd-48538.png 800w,\n/static/runtime2-71fab03e81d8c582d9f0d0d4a13d8ccd-7ad69.png 853w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>We can ONLY move to 1.x version if we have a <code class="language-text">Function app</code> with no <code class="language-text">functions</code> created. Moving between <code class="language-text">2.x</code> and <code class="language-text">3.x</code> is possible even with <code class="language-text">Function apps</code> that already have functions.</p>\n<h1>Seeing current runtime and versions</h1>\n<h2>Azure Portal</h2>\n<p>From the Azure portal, you could move into your Function App and then <code class="language-text">Configuration</code> where you get to see your application settings. And if you click on the value for <code class="language-text">FUNCTION_EXTENSION_VERSION</code> and <code class="language-text">WEBSITE_NODE_DEFAULT_VERSION</code> you will be able to see the current versions. </p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/appsetting-b082563117c3e175cbb3532b1b075c90-33242.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 45.02564102564102%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;"\n        alt="appsetting"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/appsetting-b082563117c3e175cbb3532b1b075c90-48538.png"\n        srcset="/static/appsetting-b082563117c3e175cbb3532b1b075c90-bed0f.png 200w,\n/static/appsetting-b082563117c3e175cbb3532b1b075c90-5fd34.png 400w,\n/static/appsetting-b082563117c3e175cbb3532b1b075c90-48538.png 800w,\n/static/appsetting-b082563117c3e175cbb3532b1b075c90-33242.png 975w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h2>Azure CLI</h2>\n<p>From the Azure CLI, we could run the following commands</p>\n<h3>All Application Settings</h3>\n<p>Here we use the <code class="language-text">az functionapp config appsettings list</code> and then we give the <code class="language-text">name</code> and the <code class="language-text">resource-group</code> of the function app. And this lists all the application settings.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight" data-language="json">\n      <pre class="language-json"><code class="language-json">az functionapp config appsettings list -n funcappsimon -g rgfuncappsimon</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3>Get runtime version</h3>\n<p>To get the runtime version, we make a <code class="language-text">--query</code> and get the <code class="language-text">value</code> of <code class="language-text">FUNCTIONS_EXTENSION_VERSION</code> and then pipe the value from the result array.  </p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight" data-language="json">\n      <pre class="language-json"><code class="language-json">az functionapp config appsettings list --query <span class="token string">"[?name==\'FUNCTIONS_EXTENSION_VERSION\'].value | [0]"</span> -n funcappsimon -g rgfuncappsimon</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3>Get node.js version</h3>\n<p>To get the Node.js version, we make a <code class="language-text">--query</code> and get the <code class="language-text">value</code> of <code class="language-text">WEBSITE_NODE_DEFAULT_VERSION</code> and then pipe the value from the result array.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight" data-language="json">\n      <pre class="language-json"><code class="language-json">az functionapp config appsettings list --query <span class="token string">"[?name==\'WEBSITE_NODE_DEFAULT_VERSION\'].value | [0]"</span> -n funcappsimon -g rgfuncappsimon</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h2>Azure Functions VS Code Extension</h2>\n<p>I love this extension, you could do so much. We could see application settings from here.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/extension-1076ee9bd0850b0b8e9c5b725e074c84-89b2b.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 505px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 159.80198019801978%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;"\n        alt="extension"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/extension-1076ee9bd0850b0b8e9c5b725e074c84-89b2b.png"\n        srcset="/static/extension-1076ee9bd0850b0b8e9c5b725e074c84-50b18.png 200w,\n/static/extension-1076ee9bd0850b0b8e9c5b725e074c84-275e6.png 400w,\n/static/extension-1076ee9bd0850b0b8e9c5b725e074c84-89b2b.png 505w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 505px) 100vw, 505px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h1>Next steps</h1>\n<p>I’m planning another post showing a couple of ways to migrate from 2.x to 3.x. </p>',fields:{slug:"/azfunc-v3/",prefix:"2020-02-26"},frontmatter:{title:"A brief introduction to Azure Functions 3.x",author:"Simon Ågren",category:null,tags:["azure","azurefunctions"],cover:{childImageSharp:{resize:{src:"/static/azfunc3-52663bc6c0010d24966d5439cdc6f172-160fa.png"}}}}},authornote:{id:"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/parts/author.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:"<p><strong>Simon Ågren</strong> Passionate about SharePoint and Office365. Solution Architect working as a consultant for Sogeti in Umeå, Sweden.</p>"},site:{siteMetadata:{facebook:{appId:"2263145610597628"}}}},pathContext:{slug:"/azfunc-v3/",prev:{id:"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2020-02-24--azurebot-armtemplate-keyvault/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",fields:{slug:"/azurebot-armtemplate-keyvault/",prefix:"2020-02-24"},frontmatter:{title:"Bot Framework 4 ARM template Deploy with Key Vault",category:null,tags:["botframework","azure"]}},next:{id:"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2020-02-28--azurebot-nodejs-part2/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",fields:{slug:"/azurebot-nodejs-part2/",prefix:"2020-02-28"},frontmatter:{title:"Bot Framework in Node.js - Microsoft Teams (Part 2)",category:null,tags:["botframework","nodejs","azure","msteams"]}}}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=path---azfunc-v-3-53210d480ffaffc90323.js.map